{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20181022220240|865277739","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Dave_Brat","to":"Dave Brat"}],"pages":{"43021365":{"pageid":43021365,"ns":0,"title":"Dave Brat","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-10-26T19:58:05Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{pp-move|small=yes}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Dave Brat\n|image       = Dave Brat official congressional photo.jpg\n|state       = [[Virginia]]\n|district    = {{ushr|VA|7|7th}}\n|term_start  = November 4, 2014\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Eric Cantor]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_name  = David Alan Brat\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1964|7|27}}\n|birth_place = [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = Laura Sonderman\n|children    = 2\n|education   = [[Hope College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Princeton Theological Seminary|Princeton Theological<br>Seminary]] ([[Master of Divinity|MDiv]])<br>[[American University]] ([[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])\n|website     = {{url|brat.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''David Alan Brat''' (born July 27, 1964) is an American economist and politician serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[Virginia's 7th congressional district]] since 2014. Prior to his election to Congress, Brat was a professor at [[Randolph\u2013Macon College]]. A member of the Republican Party, Brat is aligned with the [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party movement.]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/09/us/politics/dave-brat-women-virginia.html|title=In Virginia, Women Form an Insurgency to Try to Topple Republican Dave Brat|access-date=September 21, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBrat defeated [[Party leaders of the United States House of Representatives|House Majority Leader]] [[Eric Cantor]] in the district's 2014 Republican primary on June 10, 2014.<ref name=DallasNews20140610>{{cite news |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/news/politics/national-politics/20140610-house-majority-leader-eric-cantor-loses-gop-primary-to-tea-party-challenger.ece |title=House Majority Leader Eric Cantor loses GOP primary to tea-party challenger |work=Dallas Morning News |agency=Associated Press |date=June 10, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> Brat's primary victory over Cantor made him the first primary challenger to oust a sitting House Majority Leader since the position's creation in 1899, and is considered one of the biggest upsets in congressional history.<ref>{{cite news |author=Eric Linton |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/house-majority-leader-eric-cantor-defeated-tea-party-challenger-david-brat-virginia-gop-1597736 |title=House Majority Leader Eric Cantor Defeated By Tea Party Challenger David Brat In Virginia GOP Primary |publisher=International Business Times |date=June 10, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> He defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee [[Jack Trammell]] on November 4, 2014.\n\n==Early life and education==\nDavid Alan Brat was born in [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]]<ref>{{cite news |author=Gary Robertson |date=May 2014 |url=http://www.richmondmagazine.com/articles/dave-brat-republican-primary.html?page=2 |title=News and Features |work=Richmond Magazine |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> on July 27, 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/article/533729|title=Virginia-7: Dave Brat (R)|work=nationaljournal.com|accessdate=August 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Elizabeth Nolan Brown |date=June 11, 2014 |url=http://reason.com/24-7/2014/06/11/dave-brat-the-man-who-beat-eric-cantor |title=Who Is Dave Brat? Take a Look at the Ayn Rand Loving, Immigration Reform Hating, Cato Institute Referencing Man Who Beat Eric Cantor \u2013 Reason 24/7 |publisher=Reason.com |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> Brat's father, Paul, was a Doctor of [[internal medicine|Internal Medicine]]; his mother, Nancy, was employed as a [[social worker]] in [[Alma, Michigan]], where he was raised.<ref name=\"themorningsun1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.themorningsun.com/government-and-politics/20140611/alma-native-now-in-the-red-hot-heat-of-publicity |title=Alma native now in the red hot heat of publicity |publisher=Themorningsun.com |date=June 6, 2014 |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"themorningsun1\"/><ref>{{cite news |author=Juanski |date=June 11, 2014 |url=http://michigan.icito.com/tag/david-brat/ |title=David Brat Archives &#124; Michigan News |publisher=Michigan.icito.com |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.richmondmagazine.com/articles/dave-brat-republican-primary.html |title=News and Features |work=Richmond Magazine |date=December 7, 2013 |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> His family moved from Alma to Minnesota when David, the oldest of three boys, was in junior high.<ref name=\"themorningsun1\"/> Brat graduated from [[Park Center Senior High School]] in [[Brooklyn Park, Minnesota]].<ref name=\"themorningsun1\"/>\n\nBrat attended [[Hope College]] in Michigan and received a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in Business Administration in 1986; he also graduated with a [[Master's degree|Master's Degree]] in Divinity from [[Princeton Theological Seminary]] in 1990 and earned a Ph.D. in economics from [[American University]] in 1995.<ref name=education>{{cite web |title=Academic CV |author=David Brat |publisher=Randolph-Macon College |url=http://faculty.rmc.edu/dbrat/BRAT2012-CV.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Academic career==\nAfter working for [[Arthur Andersen]] and as a consultant for the [[World Bank]], Brat joined the faculty of [[Randolph\u2013Macon College]] in 1996,<ref name=education/> where he served as chair of the department of economics, and taught courses including \"Britain in the International Economy\", \"International Economic Development\", and \"Business Ethics\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://faculty.rmc.edu/dbrat/classes.html |title=Classes |publisher=Randolph-Macon College |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010 to 2012 Brat headed Randolph-Macon's BB&T Moral Foundations of Capitalism program, one of sixty similar programs and chairs in the philosophy and economics departments at United States universities devoted to the study of capitalism and morality, endowed by the [[BB&T Corporation]].<ref name=Newsweek_Pema>{{cite news |last=Levy |first=Pema |date=June 11, 2014 |title=What We Know About Dave Brat, the Tea Party Candidate Who Beat Eric Cantor |url=http://www.newsweek.com/dave-brat-beat-eric-cantor-and-hes-probably-headed-congress-254551 |publisher=Newsweek |accessdate=June 13, 2014}}</ref><ref name=YahooBBT>{{cite news |date=June 13, 2014 |last=Santoli |first=Michael |title=The big bank that blessed Brat's upset of Eric Cantor |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/blogs/breakout/the-big-bank-that-blessed-brat-s-upset-of-eric-cantor-125146311.html |publisher=Yahoo Finance |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clemson.edu/capitalism/capres/bbtp.html |title=Clemson Institute for the Study of Capitalism |publisher=Clemson University |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref><ref name=RMC-CV>{{cite web|title=David Brat Faculty CV|url=http://faculty.rmc.edu/dbrat/2012professionalActivity.html|website=Randolph-Macon College|publisher=Randolph-Macon College|accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 Brat was appointed by Virginia governor [[Tim Kaine]] to the Governor's Advisory Board of Economists, a position he continues to hold. He has also served on the board of directors of the [[Richmond Metropolitan Authority]], and on the advisory board of the Virginia Public Access Project.<ref name=\"RMC-CV\"/>\n\n==Special legislative assistant==\nFrom 2005 to 2011, Brat worked as a special [[legislative assistant]] to Virginia state senator [[Walter Stosch]] in the area of [[higher education]].<ref name=education/> In 2006 he was appointed by Democratic governor [[Tim Kaine]] to serve on a bipartisan economic advisory council. He was later reappointed by Republican Governor [[Bob McDonnell]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsmax.com/Politics/Cantor-defeat-reason-Brat/2014/06/10/id/576307/|title=Virginians Felt Cantor's DC Power Did Little to Help Them|last=Gizzi|first=John|date=June 10, 2014|work=NewsMax|accessdate=September 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Elections==\n===2011 Virginia House of Delegates campaign ===\nIn August 2011, Brat announced he was running for the [[Virginia House of Delegates]] seat for the 56th district. There was no primary, and six Republican leaders met and chose [[Peter Farrell (politician)|Peter Farrell]] as the Republican nominee in the November 2011 general election.<ref>{{cite web |author=Michelle Stanley |date=August 18, 2011 |publisher=Virginia Right |url=http://www.varight.com/news/dr-david-brat-seeks-56th-house-of-delegate-seat/ |title=Dr. David Brat seeks 56th House of Delegate Seat |accessdate=June 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2014 U.S. House campaign===\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in Virginia, 2014#District 7}}\n\n====Republican primary====\n\n[[File:Dave Brat by Gage Skidmore.jpg|right|thumb|Dave Brat speaking at an event in February 2016.]]\nBrat ran against House Majority Leader [[Eric Cantor]] for the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nomination for [[Virginia's 7th congressional district]] and defeated Cantor by a 12-point margin.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2014/06/10/house-majority-leader-eric-cantor-loses-virginia-gop-primary-ap-reports/|title=Cantor upset in Virginia GOP primary by Tea Party backed challenger|work=Fox News|author=Chad Pergram, Associated Press.|date=June 10, 2014|accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> Brat was outspent by Cantor 40 to 1: Cantor spent over $5 million, while Brat raised $200,000 and did not spend all of it.<ref name=\"MemoliLATimes06112014\">{{cite news |last=Memoli |first=Michael A. |url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/politicsnow/la-pn-eric-cantor-dave-brat-primary-20140611-story.html |title=Eric Cantor upset: How Dave Brat pulled off a historic political coup] |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=June 11, 2014 |accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mascaro |first=Lisa |author2=Michael A. Memoli |author3=Mark Z. Barabak |url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/politicsnow/la-na-pn-cantor-loses-to-tea-party-challenger-20140610-story.html |title=Washington reels as House's Eric Cantor loses to tea party challenger |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=June 11, 2014 |accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref> Brat's primary campaign was managed by 23-year-old Zachary Werrell.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/meet-dave-brats-23-year-old-campaign-manager/article/2549565 |title=Meet Dave Brat's 23 Year Old Campaign Manager |work=Washington Examiner |author= Betsy Woodruff |date=June 10, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> An analysis of campaign filings conducted by the [[Center for Responsive Politics]] concluded that Brat did not receive any donations from [[political action committees]], noting \"it's almost impossible to profile Brat's typical donor, because he had so few.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.opensecrets.org/news/2014/06/dave-versus-goliath-by-the-numbers/ |title=Dave Versus Goliath, By the Numbers |last=Choma |first=Russ |date=June 11, 2014 |website=opensecrets.org |publisher=Center for Responsive Politics |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> Brat's win was notable,<ref name=NYT06102014>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/11/us/politics/eric-cantor-loses-gop-primary.html |title=Eric Cantor Defeated by David Brat, Tea Party Challenger, in G.O.P. Primary Upset |work=The New York Times |last=Martin |first=Jonathan |date=June 11, 2014 |page=A1 |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/no-2-house-republican-eric-cantor-defeated-in-virginia-primary-upset-1402445714|title=Eric Cantor Loses to Tea Party's David Brat in Virginia Primary|work=The Wall Street Journal|author=Janet Hook and Kristina Peterson|date=June 10, 2014|accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-politics/eric-cantor-faces-tea-party-challenge-tuesday/2014/06/10/17da5d20-f092-11e3-bf76-447a5df6411f_story.html|title=Eric Cantor succumbs to tea party challenger Tuesday|work=The Washington Post|author= Robert Costa, Laura Vozzella and David A. Fahrenthold|date=June 10, 2014|accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> as it was the first time a sitting House Majority Leader was defeated in his primary race since the position was created in 1899.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/washington-is-caught-totally-off-guard-by-cantor-loss-023046579.html |title=Washington is caught totally off guard by Cantor loss |work=Yahoo News |author= Chris Moody |date=June 11, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nCompared with Cantor, described as aloof, Brat was characterized as knowing how to work a crowd.<ref>J.S.,  [https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2014/06/virginia-politics \"Who Is David Brat?\"], Democracy in America blog, ''[[The Economist]]'',  June 16, 2014.  Retrieved October 29, 2014.</ref> He ran an anti-establishment campaign criticizing Cantor's position on [[Illegal immigration to the United States|illegal immigration]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/615/the-beginning-of-now|title=The Beginning of Now|work=This American Life|access-date=April 29, 2017|language=en}}</ref> government bailouts and budget deals while frequently invoking God and the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]] in his speeches. During the campaign, Cantor criticized Brat as a \"liberal professor\" who had strong ties to [[Tim Kaine]], Virginia's former [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] governor and current junior Senator.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/208922-cantor-goes-down-to-tea-party-upset |title=Cantor out in Tea Party shocker |date=June 10, 2014 |website=thehill.com |publisher=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBrat ran well to Cantor's right, complaining that Cantor had a \"[[crony capitalism|crony-capitalist]] mentality\", putting the interests of the corporate sector ahead of small businesses.<ref>{{cite news |last=Parkinson |first=John |title=Dave Brat: Meet the Candidate Who Beat Eric Cantor |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/dave-brat-meet-candidate-beat-eric-cantor/story?id=24081628 |publisher=ABC News |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> [[Radio talk show]] host [[Laura Ingraham]] endorsed Brat's candidacy and hosted a rally with him in a Richmond suburb.<ref name=DallasNews20140610/> Brat was also supported by radio talk show host [[Mark Levin]]<ref name=NY-11.6.14>{{cite news |last=Cassidy |first=John |title=Cantor Loses, and Washington Goes Ape |url=http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/johncassidy/2014/06/eric-cantor-loses-to-david-brat.html|accessdate=June 11, 2014|publisher=The New Yorker|date=June 11, 2014}}</ref> and [[Ann Coulter]].<ref name=\"WP-Bump 10.6.14\">{{cite news |last=Bump |first=Philip |title=David Brat just beat Eric Cantor. Who is he?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2014/06/10/david-brat-just-beat-eric-cantor-who-is-he/|accessdate=June 11, 2014|publisher=The Washington Post|date=June 10, 2014}}</ref> [[Chris Peace]], a state legislator who collaborated with Brat on state budget issues at Randolph-Macon College, stated that Brat was inspired to run for Congress because of \"His passion for the structure of government and belief in free markets.\"<ref name=NYT140612>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/12/us/politics/david-brat-waged-solo-fight-against-eric-cantor.html |title=Once Snubbed, David Brat Turns the Tables |last=Steinhauer |first=Jennifer |date=June 12, 2014 |work=[[The New York Times]] |page=A1 |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBrat's victory was described in the press as exposing a \"deep schism\" in the Republican party between its conservative base and its business wing, as well as a split between establishment Republicans and [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party insurgents]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Matea|last=Gold|authorlink= |coauthors= |title=How national tea party groups missed the David Brat boat |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2014/06/10/how-national-tea-party-groups-missed-the-david-brat-boat/ |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=June 10, 2014 |accessdate=June 12, 2014|quote=Brat's victory underlined the deep schism in the party between its conservative base and its business wing. }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Tea party stuns GOP leader Eric Cantor|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2014/06/10/4968350/tea-party-stuns-gop-leader-eric.html#.U5s5By8Wdt8|publisher=Charlotte Observer|accessdate=June 13, 2014|quote=Brat also got help from the more conservative wing of the Virginia Republican Party, which for years has been split between more establishment Republicans and tea party activists.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Emboldened after Cantor, tea party crows|url=https://news.yahoo.com/emboldened-cantor-tea-party-crows-202904376--election.html |publisher=Yahoo News |accessdate=June 13, 2014|quote=The GOP is expected to retain control of the House, but Brat's pounding of Cantor Tuesday ripped open the establishment-vs.-insurgent split that's plagued the party since the 2010 elections.}}</ref> Some libertarian oriented groups, such as the Virginia Liberty Party, backed Brat.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Virginia Liberty Party 2014 General Election Endorsements|url=http://www.virginialibertyparty.com/2014/11/the-virginia-liberty-party-2014-general.html |website=Virginia Liberty Party |accessdate=November 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBrat received support from, and gave credit for his win to, local Tea Party groups in Virginia, but received no funding or endorsement from national Tea Party organizations.<ref name=NYT06102014/> Brat has not self-identified with the [[Tea Party movement]].<ref>{{cite news |first=|last=|authorlink= |coauthors= |title=How David Brat Won |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/06/2014-virginia-primary-david-brat-107700_Page2.html |work=[[Politico]] |date=June 11, 2014 |accessdate=June 12, 2014 }}</ref> Ron Rapoport, a political scientist at the [[College of William & Mary]], has said Brat may be correctly identified as a \"tea partier\" only if the term is used as a catchall for \"anti-establishment activist\", while [[John Judis]] has opined that Brat could more correctly be described as a \"[[right-wing populism|right-wing populist]]\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Grier |last=Peter |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Is David Brat really a tea partier? |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/DC-Decoder/Decoder-Buzz/2014/0611/Is-David-Brat-really-a-tea-partyer-video |work=[[The Christian Science Monitor]] |date=June 11, 2014 |accessdate=June 12, 2014 }}</ref> Matea Gold in ''[[The Washington Post]]'' stated, \"the fact that Brat took off without the help of those organizations [national tea party groups] now makes it harder for them to claim his victory as their own.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Matea|last=Gold|authorlink= |coauthors= |title=How national tea party groups missed the David Brat boat |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2014/06/10/how-national-tea-party-groups-missed-the-david-brat-boat/ |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=June 10, 2014 |accessdate=June 12, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nAlthough the national media were shocked at Brat's victory, Richmond-area media outlets had received signs well before the primary that Cantor was in trouble.<ref name=Blindspot>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/16/business/media/eric-cantors-defeat-exposed-a-beltway-journalism-blind-spot.html|title=Eric Cantor\u2019s Defeat Exposed a Beltway Journalism Blind Spot|last=Carr|first=David|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 16, 2014}}</ref>  The ''[[Richmond Times-Dispatch]]'' reported two weeks before the primary that a number of Cantor's constituents felt he took them for granted.  The ''Times-Dispatch'' also revealed that Cantor's attempt to brand Brat as a liberal professor actually made more people turn out for Brat.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.richmond.com/news/state-regional/virginia-politics/schapiro-in-new-kent-brat-backers-hope-to-hold-cantor/article_dff230e0-d76a-599d-992e-3bb000efe560.html|title=In New Kent, Brat Backers Hope To Hold Cantor Accountable|last=Schapiro|first=Jeff|publisher=[[Richmond Times-Dispatch]]|date=May 24, 2014}}</ref> ''The Chesterfield Observer,'' a local paper serving [[Chesterfield County, Virginia|Chesterfield County]]\u2014roughly half of which is in the 7th\u2014reported that Tea Party-aligned candidates had won several victories there, and at least one Cantor loyalist believed Tea Party supporters smelled \"blood in the water.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chesterfieldobserver.com/news/2014-06-04/Front_Page/Retreading_the_GOP.html|title=Retreading the GOP?|last=McConnell|first=Jim|publisher=The Chesterfield Observer|date=June 4, 2014}}</ref> One local reporter told David Carr of ''[[The New York Times]]'' that many constituents believed Cantor was arrogant and unapproachable. However, due to massive cutbacks, the race was severely underpolled by local media.  Few Capitol Hill reporters were willing to go to Cantor's district, for fear that they would be out of Washington in case a major story broke.<ref name=Blindspot/>\n\n====General election====\nBrat faced Democratic nominee [[Jack Trammell]], another professor at Randolph-Macon, and James Carr, the Libertarian candidate, in the November [[United States House of Representatives elections in Virginia, 2014|general election]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Andrew Prokop |url=https://www.vox.com/2014/6/10/5798686/dave-brat-and-his-democratic-general-election-opponent-are-both |title=Dave Brat and his Democratic general election opponent are both professors from the same college |publisher=Vox.com |date=June 10, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> Brat was favored because of the 7th's significant Republican leaning (the district has a [[Cook Partisan Voting Index]] of R+10, showing it to be the most Republican district in eastern Virginia).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2014/06/11/who-is-dave-brat-who-beat-cantor/10316907|title= Who is Dave Brat, GOP giant-killer who took down Eric Cantor?|last=Cania|first=Catalina|work=[[USA Today]]|date=June 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an article in ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', Cantor announced plans to aid Brat by resigning from the [[United States Congress]] on August 18, so that a special election could be held on the same day as the general election. Thus the winner, in a race in which Brat was favored, would take office with the perquisite of seniority over other first-term Republicans elected in the 2014 midterm elections and with the ability to participate in the lame-duck session of Congress.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kenny|first1=Steve|title=In effort to aid successor, Eric Cantor to leave House early|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2014/08/01/cantor-majority-leader-leave-congress-early/5xbRmhsIIKfX59HEYWOTLL/story.html|website=www.bostonglobe.com|publisher=The Boston Globe|accessdate=August 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBrat defeated Trammell in that election, with 60.83% of the vote to Trammell's 36.95%.  Libertarian candidate James Carr finished third, with 2.09% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|title=After Toppling Eric Cantor, Dave Brat Wins His Seat|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/11/04/after-toppling-eric-cantor-dave-brat-wins-his-seat-in-virginia|publisher=U.S. News|accessdate=November 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2016 U.S. House campaign===\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in Virginia, 2016#}}\n\nBrat defeated Democrat Eileen Bedell with 57.7% of the vote in the general election held on November 8, 2016.\n\n===2018 U.S. House campaign===\n\nUp until October 13, 2017, the district was rated \"Safe Republican\" by the non-partisan ''[[The Cook Political Report|Cook Political Report]]''. On October 13, 2017, ''Cook'' updated the race rating to \"Likely Republican.\" On February 8, 2018, the race rating was changed to \"Leans Republican,\" and on July 7, 2018, the race was rated a \"Toss-up.\" Brat's Democratic opponent is [[Abigail Spanberger]], a former CIA officer who grew up in the district.<ref>https://www.cookpolitical.com/analysis/house/virginia-house/va-07-brat-moves-lean-republican-toss#.Wz-48PMRCbI.twitter</ref>\n\nDuring an October 2018 debate, Brat characterized his opponent, Spanberger, as a disciple of Nancy Pelosi. Brat referred so often to Pelosi that it started to draw laughs. According to the ''Washington Post'', a conservative estimate is that he referred to Pelosi 25 times.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-politics/rep-brat-and-democrat-spanberger-tangle-in-first--and-likely-only--debate/2018/10/15/03d6615c-d08f-11e8-8c22-fa2ef74bd6d6_story.html|title=Rep. Brat and Democrat Spanberger tangle in first \u2014 and probably only \u2014 debate|last=|first=|date=|website=Washington Post|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-10-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/nancy-pelosi-abigail-spanberger-dave-brat_us_5bc52fa4e4b055bc9478f684|title=GOP Congressman Somehow Manages To Mention Nancy Pelosi 21 Times In A Debate|last=Fuller|first=Matt|date=2018-10-16|work=Huffington Post|access-date=2018-10-16|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\nDave Brat was sworn in on November 12, 2014 to finish Eric Cantor's term.<ref>[http://www.dailyprogress.com/news/local/dave-brat-takes-office-as-eric-i-cantor-s-replacement/article_aaf04078-6ae2-11e4-af54-73b777267c40.html \"Dave Brat Takes Office As Eric I. Cantor's Replacement in 7th District\"]. ''The Daily Progress'', November 12, 2014. Retrieved November 13, 2014.</ref>\n\nOn January 6, 2015, Brat was one of twenty-five House Republicans to vote against [[John Boehner]]'s re-election as [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives]]. Boehner, who needed at least 205 votes, was re-elected with 216 votes.<ref>French, Lauren (January 6, 2015) \u2013 [http://www.politico.com/story/2015/01/hell-no-caucus-daniel-webster-114008.html \"Hell No Caucus Sees Silver Lining In Loss\"]. ''POLITICO''. Retrieved February 26, 2015.</ref> Though Brat supported Boehner earlier, he reversed his support after the House GOP leadership did not allow him to make an amendment to block a controversial executive order signed by President [[Barack Obama]] in a spending bill.<ref>Camia, Catalina (January 5, 2015) \u2013 [http://onpolitics.usatoday.com/2015/01/05/boehner-speaker-vote-brat/ \"Rep. Dave Brat: Boehner Won't Have My Support\"]. ''USA Today''. Retrieved February 26, 2015.</ref>\n\nBrat faced heckling by 150 people at a \"raucous\" town hall meeting in the small town of [[Blackstone, Virginia]], on February 21, 2017. Some questioned Brat on the border wall, health care, and President Trump\u2019s policies.<ref name=\"WP_townhall_2017\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-politics/the-women-got-up-in-brats-grill-and-then-some/2017/02/21/9e8db1fa-f855-11e6-be05-1a3817ac21a5_story.html |title=The women got up in Brat\u2019s grill, and then some |newspaper=''The Washington Post'' |author=Jenna Portnoy |location=Blackstone, Virginia|date=February 21, 2017 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> Several of Brat's supporters left the meeting early.<ref name=\"WP_townhall_2017\" /> Brat was criticized for not meeting with his constituents because he claimed there were paid protesters among them. On January 28, at a meeting held at Hanover Tavern with \"the GOP-friendly audience\", he had lamented that, \"[s]ince Obamacare and these issues have come up, the women are in my grill no matter where I go. They come up \u2014 'When is your next town hall?' And believe me, it\u2019s not to give positive input.\"<ref name=\"WP_grill_2017\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-politics/va-rep-dave-brat-the-women-are-in-my-grill-no-matter-where-i-go/2017/01/31/41f89be4-e7fc-11e6-80c2-30e57e57e05d_story.html?tid=a_inl |title=The women got up in Brat\u2019s grill, and then some |newspaper=''The Washington Post'' |author=Jenna Portnoy |location=Virginia|date=January 31, 2017 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> He also urged his fellow conservatives at the Tavern, \"to write newspaper articles because \"we\u2019re getting hammered.\"<ref name=\"Richmond_Brat_women_2017\">{{cite news |url=http://www.richmond.com/news/virginia/meet-the-women-who-are-up-in-dave-brat-s/article_c41b47cb-736a-58e4-9448-b99e8f7bac11.html |title=Meet the women who are up in Dave Brat's grill |authors=Vanessa Remmers and Patrick Wilson |newspaper=''Richmond Times-Dispatch'' |date=February 19, 2017|accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> Brat had considered running in Virginia's 2018 Senate election.<ref name=\"realclearpolitics_2016\">{{cite news |url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2016/10/04/gop_starts_to_eye_race_to_replace_kaine_in_senate_131960.html |title=GOP Starts to Eye Race to Replace Kaine in Senate |publisher=RealClearPolitics |author= James Arkin |date=October 4, 2016 |accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> He is a member of the [[Freedom Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=What is the House Freedom Caucus, and who\u2019s in it?|author=|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/10/20/house-freedom-caucus-what-is-it-and-whos-in-it/|format=|publisher=Pew research center|date=October 20, 2015|accessdate=October 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, the ''[[Richmond Times-Dispatch]]'' reported that a campaign staffer was using her personal Facebook profile to debate commenters on his Facebook posts.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.richmond.com/news/virginia/government-politics/she-argued-with-liberals-on-rep-dave-brat-s-facebook/article_ab66d673-1b51-5278-8fee-3011757394dd.html|title=She argued with liberals on Rep. Dave Brat's Facebook page. Then they found out he was paying her.|last=Times-Dispatch|first=VANESSA REMMERS AND PATRICK WILSON Richmond|work=Richmond Times-Dispatch|access-date=November 17, 2017|language=en}}</ref> The woman did not identify herself as a paid campaign staffer.<ref name=\":1\" /> When asked about this, Brat said, \"Her job is to clarify issues. And put out my policy positions from my vantage point. It\u2019s not to argue with people.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> Brat had another run in with social media on March 1, 2018, when it was discovered that his campaign Twitter account had \"liked\" several controversial tweets, including one that questioned whether one of the survivors of the Parkland school shooting, David Hogg was a \"crisis actor\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/brats-twitter-account-removes-likes-of-conspiracy-tweets|title=Brat\u2019s Office Removes \u2018Likes\u2019 of Controversial Parkland Tweets|last=Garcia|first=Eric|date=March 2, 2018|work=Roll Call|access-date=March 21, 2018|last2=Garcia|first2=Eric|language=en}}</ref> After an outcry from concerned constituents, Brat's office issued a statement that attributed the likes to a campaign staffer when they believed they were logged onto their personal account. He also stated that safeguards were being put in place to ensure it did not happen again.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.richmond.com/news/virginia/government-politics/rep-dave-brat-s-twitter-account-removes-likes-of-controversial/article_424fbe88-1eb0-5218-bac6-05a1efb1ec1e.html|title=Rep. Dave Brat's Twitter account removes likes of controversial tweets after outcry|last=Times-Dispatch|first=PATRICK WILSON Richmond|work=Richmond Times-Dispatch|access-date=March 21, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on the Budget|Committee on the Budget]]'''\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Committee on Education and the Workforce]]'''\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education|Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education]]\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Workforce Protections|Subcommittee on Workforce Protections]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Small Business|Committee on Small Business]]'''\n**[[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Agriculture, Energy and Trade|Subcommittee on Agriculture, Energy and Trade]]\n**[[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Tax and Capital Access|Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Tax and Capital Access]] (Chairman)\n\n==Economic views ==\n{{Tone|section|date=September 2015}}\nBrat asserts that culture matters in economic markets. He believes that the culture that produced [[Adam Smith]] was a [[Protestant culture]] and that fact and the ethics of that culture are important in understanding market efficiency.<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Brien |first=Matt |date=June 11, 2014|title=Dave Brat's unorthodox economics: Adam Smith 'was from a red state'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2014/06/11/heres-what-david-brat-thinks-about-economics|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=June 13, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=David Brat|title=Adam Smith's God: the End of Economics|year=2005|url=http://faculty.rmc.edu/dbrat/researchpapers/2005VAEAdamSmithPaper.doc|deadurl=unfit|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060910171001/http://faculty.rmc.edu/dbrat/researchpapers/2005VAEAdamSmithPaper.doc|archivedate=September 10, 2006}}</ref> Brat advocated that Christians should more forcefully support free-market [[capitalism]] and behave more altruistically, in the manner of [[Jesus]], so that \"we would not need the government to backstop every action we take.\"<ref name=\"WashWireWSJ06102014\">{{cite news|author=Reid J. Epstein|date=June 11, 2014|title=David Brat's Writings: Hitler's Rise 'Could All Happen Again'|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2014/06/11/david-brats-writings-hitlers-rise-could-all-happen-again|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=June 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Kevin Roose in a ''New York'' Magazine article, Brat \"sees [[Free market|free-market]] economics as being intricately linked to ethics and faith and he makes the case that Adam Smith's [[invisible hand]] theory, should be seen in the context of [[Christianity]]\".<ref name=NYMagRoose06122014>{{cite news|last=Roose|first=Kevin|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2014/06/david-brat-christian-rights-favorite-economist.html |title=David Brat Just Became the Christian Right's Favorite Economist |publisher=New York Magazine|date=June 11, 2014|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> Furthering the central theme of [[Max Weber]]'s seminal book ''[[The Protestant Ethic and the Spirit of Capitalism]],'' Brat argues in his 2004 paper ''Economic Growth and Institutions: The Rise and Fall of the Protestant Ethic?'' that \"institutions such as religion, democracy and government anti-diversion policies all significantly enhance a country's long-run economic performance,\" and concludes that \"the religion variable may be the strongest ex ante, exogenous institutional variable in the literature.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Noah|first=Timothy|date=June 11, 2014|title=Dave Brat: Christianity is the key to prosperity|url=http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/david-brat-economics-christianity|publisher=MSNBC.com|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn a paper titled ''Is Growth Exogenous? Taking Bernanke Seriously'', Brat criticized [[Federal Reserve]] chairman [[Ben Bernanke]], asserting that Bernanke's work on economic growth overlooks religious institutions \u2013 in particular Protestant \u2013 in a country's economic growth, and that while savings rates, population growth, and human capital accumulation help drive economic growth, the larger factor is \"the Protestant religious establishment\", which Bernanke ignores.<ref>{{cite news|last=Zumbrum|first=Josh|date=June 11, 2014|title=David Brat to Bernanke: Don't Underestimate the Value of Protestants|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/economics/2014/06/11/david-brat-to-bernanke-dont-underestimate-the-value-of-protestants|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBrat has blamed the rise of [[Adolf Hitler]] in Germany on the lack of \"unified resistance\", adding, \"I have the sinking feeling that it could all happen again, quite easily.\"<ref name=WashWireWSJ06102014/> Brat believes that countries with Protestant pasts have economic advantages over countries that do not, and that [[Protestantism]] \"provides an efficient set of property rights and encourages a modern set of economic incentives\" that often lead to \"positive economic performance\".<ref name=NYMagRoose06122014/> He believes in [[Christ]] as a transformer of [[culture]], and that capitalism is the key to world transformation, which can be achieved when capitalism and [[Christianity]] merge; if people follow the gospel, and as a consequence behave more morally, he argues, then the markets will improve.<ref name=TimesBiblicalViews/>\n\nZack Beauchamp from ''[[Vox Media]]'' has said that Brat believes that \"most economists are motivated by philosophy rather than science: they're secretly [[Utilitarianism|utilitarians]] who believe that the goal of public policy is to produce the greatest good for the greatest number.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Beauchamp|first=Zack|date=June 10, 2014|title=The guy who beat Eric Cantor penned a scathing, seemingly unpublished book about the economics profession|url=https://www.vox.com/2014/6/10/5798708/brat-academic-research|publisher=Vox|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> Although Brat has stated he does not identify as a [[Objectivism (Ayn Rand)|Randian]], he has acknowledged having been influenced by [[Ayn Rand]]'s novel ''[[Atlas Shrugged]]'' and has expressed appreciation of Ayn Rand's case for [[human freedom]] and [[capitalism]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Woodruff|first=Betsy|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/367690/eric-cantors-challenger-right-betsy-woodruff|title=Eric Cantor's Challenger from the Right|work=National Review|publisher=National Review Online|date=January 6, 2014|accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n''[[Conservative Review]]'' has graded Brat's voting record an A with a Liberty Score of 100%. Brat is one of two Republican representatives to receive this highest possible grade out of 247 Republicans in the House of Representatives, along with [[Jim Jordan (U.S. politician)|Jim Jordan]] of Ohio.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.conservativereview.com/scorecard|title=Conservative Review - Scorecard|work=conservativereview.com|accessdate=August 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Economy===\nBrat has promised to vote against raising the [[United States debt ceiling|debt ceiling]] for the first five years he is in Congress,<ref name=\"Esquire_Brat_Lesson\">{{cite news | url=http://www.esquire.com/blogs/politics/The_Dave_Brat_Lesson | title=A Stunning Victory for the Tea Party, and What It Means | publisher=Esquire | date=June 11, 2014 | accessdate=June 12, 2014 | author=Pierce, Charleps P.}}</ref> and he attacked Cantor during the primary campaign for voting to end the [[United States federal government shutdown of 2013|federal government shutdown of 2013]].<ref name=\"Esquire_Brat_Lesson\"/> Brat advocates for an end to [[tax credit]]s, deductions and loopholes, and calls for a more flat and efficient tax code.<ref name=\"WSJKimStrassel\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-strassel-what-dave-brat-taught-conservatives-1402614856|title=What Dave Brat Taught Conservatives|last=Strassel|first=Kim|accessdate=June 12, 2014|publisher=The Wall Street Journal}}{{subscription required}}</ref> Brat has indicated he opposed TARP, the [[Troubled Asset Relief Program]] of 2008, and has stated that, if elected, he would \"vote against bills that benefit big business over small business\".<ref name=\"ofwe\" /> He has stated: \"I'm not against business. I'm against big business in bed with big government.\"<ref name=\"Fang-11.6.14\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/180195/eric-cantors-opponent-beat-him-calling-out-gop-corruption#|title=Eric Cantor's Opponent Beat Him by Calling Out GOP Corruption|last=Fang|first=Lee|date=June 11, 2014|accessdate=June 12, 2014|publisher=The Nation}}</ref>\n\nBrat supported President Trump's trade policies, arguing that Americans benefitted from re-negotiating NAFTA and that while tariffs on China would cause short-term harms, they would ultimately lead to \"zero tariffs.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Education===\nBrat opposes federally driven education policies such as the [[Common Core State Standards Initiative|Common Core]] curriculum and [[No Child Left Behind Act|No Child Left Behind]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Rosenwald |first=Michael |title=Capitalism and ethics drive Brat's world view |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-politics/capitalism-ethics-drive-brats-world-view/2014/06/11/17497fc0-f188-11e3-914c-1fbd0614e2d4_story.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=June 13, 2014 |date=June 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Ethics reform===\nHis decision to enter the Republican primary was driven largely by Cantor's role in weakening congressional ethics reform. Brat stated: \"If you want to find out the smoking gun in this campaign, just go Google and type the [[STOCK Act]] and [[CNN]] and [[Eric Cantor]].\"<ref name=Fang-11.6.14 />\n\n===Healthcare===\nBrat opposes the Affordable Care Act (Obamacare).<ref>{{cite news |last=Brat |first=Dave |title=Brat: A challenger for the 7th District |url=http://www.timesdispatch.com/opinion/their-opinion/columnists-blogs/guest-columnists/brat-a-challenger-for-the-th-district/article_20886f1d-bae2-5764-94bc-52494877c27a.html |work=Times Dispatch |accessdate=June 13, 2014 |date=June 6, 2014}}</ref> In March 2017, Brat said that he opposed the initial version of the American Health Care Act, which was the GOP's replacement plan for the Affordable Care Act (Obamacare), and that he intended to vote against it in the [[United States House Committee on the Budget|House Budget Committee]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/03/dave-brat-gop-obamacare-repeal-bill-committee-vote-236093|title=Obamacare repeal bill faces tough committee vote Thursday|work=POLITICO|access-date=March 15, 2017}}</ref> On May 4, 2017, Brat voted to repeal the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare) and pass the revised version of the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|American Health Care Act]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/ahca-house-vote/|title=How the House voted to pass the GOP health-care bill|website=Washington Post|access-date=May 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/04/politics/house-health-care-vote/index.html|title=How every member voted on health care bill|last=Staff|first=C. N. N.|website=CNN|access-date=May 4, 2017}}</ref> Brat said that the bill would contain protections for preexisting conditions and lead to lower prices; ''The Washington Post'' noted that the bill would have allowed insurers to charge higher premiums for individuals with preexisting conditions, and that an analysis by the Congressional Budget Office estimated that average health care premiums would increase as a result of the bill (more so for older Americans).<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nDuring his 2018 re-election campaign, Brat falsely claimed that ''The Washington Post'' fact-checker had given \"four pinocchios\" to his opponent Abigail Spanberger for claims she made about Brat's position on health care. ''The Washington Post'' fact-checker asked Brat to comment on his misrepresentation but did not receive a response.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2018/10/16/virginia-congressman-misrepresents-washington-post-fact-check-debate/|title=Analysis {{!}} Virginia congressman misrepresents Washington Post fact check in debate|last=|first=|date=|website=Washington Post|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-10-16}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign policy and defense===\nBrat has called for the [[National Security Agency]] to end bulk collection of phone records and has stated his support for statutory protections for e-mail privacy. He has argued that domestic intelligence activities have \"spun out of control\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Brian |last=Fung |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Eric Cantor was a friend of the NSA. The guy who beat him hates it. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-switch/wp/2014/06/11/eric-cantor-was-a-friend-of-the-nsa-the-guy-who-beat-him-hates-it/ |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=June 11, 2014 |accessdate=June 12, 2014 }}</ref> and that \"the NSA's indiscriminate collection of data on all Americans is a disturbing violation of our [[Fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourth Amendment]] right to privacy.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/2014/6/10/5798554/eric-cantors-loss-is-bad-news-for-the-nsa |title=Eric Cantor's loss is bad news for the NSA |last=Lee |first=Timothy |date=June 10, 2014 |website=vox.com |publisher=Vox |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> In an April 21, 2015, interview with radio talk show host Rusty Humphries, Brat claimed that the terrorist group ISIS has set up a base in [[Texas]]. \"In our country it looks like we have an ISIS center in Texas now...You can't make up what a terrible problem this is.\" After the Texas Department of Public Safety responded that there was no substantiation for the claim, Brat's office said that he had really meant to say Mexico, not Texas, citing the conservative group [[Judicial Watch]], which declined to provide any substantiation for its report.<ref>Dylan Baddour, [http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/texas/article/U-S-Rep-says-ISIS-operates-Texas-base-6243149.php \"U.S Rep. says ISIS operates Texas base\"], ''Houston Chronicle'', May 5, 2015 (Updated May 8, 2015), Retrieved May 8, 2015</ref>\n\n===Immigration ===\nBrat supported President [[Donald Trump]]'s 2017 [[Executive Order 13769|executive order]] to temporarily curtail immigration from the Muslim-majority nations of [[Iran]], [[Iraq]], [[Libya]], [[Somalia]], [[Sudan]], [[Syria]], and [[Yemen]] until better screening methods are devised. Brat stated that \"the temporary halt on migration from seven countries will last only a few months until we have solid vetting procedures in place, and that \"these seven countries with a temporary travel ban have been identified by both the Obama administration and our intelligence agencies as being the greatest threat to our national security because they have a history of training, harboring, and exporting terrorism.\"<ref name=\"Blake1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2017/01/29/republicans-on-trump-travel-ban/|title=Coffman, Gardner join Republicans against President Trump\u2019s travel ban; here\u2019s where the rest stand|last1=Blake|first1=Aaron|website=Denver Post|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Brat said that [[Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals|Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals (DACA)]], which provided temporary stay for unauthorized immigrants brought to the United as minors, would allow the minors to \"bring in their entire extended family once they reach a certain status,\" and could up to 4 million additional immigrants.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2017/sep/15/dave-brat/rep-dave-brats-false-claim-about-daca-chain-migrat/|title=Rep. Dave Brat: DACA recipients lead to chain migration|work=@politifact|access-date=September 17, 2017|language=en}}</ref> PolitiFact disputed Brat's 4 million figure.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Social issues===\nIn 2011, Brat criticized the political right for simultaneously advancing the pursuit of individual liberty while pushing laws restricting [[abortion]], [[LGBT rights|gay rights]] and [[gambling]], and the political left for simultaneously supporting progressive liberal individualism while coercing others to \"fund every social program under the sun\".<ref name=WashWireWSJ06102014/> Brat's website states that he supports \"the life of every child, both born and unborn.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Dave Brat Supports Life |url=https://davebrat.com/prolife/ |publisher=Dave Brat for Congress |accessdate=June 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Social Security and Medicare===\nBrat has criticized both major parties' approach to [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] and [[Department of Social Security|Social Security]], stating, \"neither side of the aisle will talk about the most important issues because that is going to involve pain.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Walsh |first=Deirdre |date=June 11, 2014 |title=Cantor challenger, Dave Brat, 'shocked' as results rolled in |url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/06/11/politics/brat-cantor-upset-win/ |publisher=CNN |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> Brat advocates \"market-based reforms\" to these programs,<ref>{{cite news |last=Vultaggio |first=Maria |date=June 10, 2014 |title=Who Is David Brat? Twitter Reacts To Eric Cantor's Tea Party Challenger |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/who-david-brat-twitter-reacts-eric-cantors-tea-party-challenger-1597752|work=International Business Times |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> arguing individuals ought not to receive more from programs than they have paid into them.<ref>{{cite news |last=Digby Parton |first=Heather |date=June 12, 2014 |title=Libertarians' scary, new guru: Why Dave Brat is no populist hero |url=http://www.salon.com/2014/06/12/libertarians_have_a_new_guru_why_dave_brat_is_no_populist_hero/ |publisher=Salon |accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref> Brat has suggested age- and means-based reform to the eligibility of claimants for mandatory entitlements as a means to avoid insolvency.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Susan |date=December 27, 2015 |title=Rep. Dave Brat: 'We Have a Fundamental Budget Problem Coming Our Way in 11 Years' |url=http://www.cnsnews.com/news/article/susan-jones/rep-dave-brat-we-have-fundamental-budget-problem-coming-our-way-11-years |work=CNSNews.com |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Term limits===\nBrat is a proponent of term limits for members of Congress. He has pledged to serve a maximum of 12 years (six terms) in Congress.<ref name=\"ofwe\">{{cite web |url=http://davebratforcongress.com/issues/ |title=Issues |publisher=Dave Brat for Congress |accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin no change\n  | title= Virginia's 7th congressional district Republican primary, 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://electionresults.virginia.gov/resultsSW.aspx?type=CON&map=CTY|title=Unofficial Results \u2013 Primary Election \u2013 June 10, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=December 22, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |ca